# Maxim Kapelina, Layke Martin, Sahib Srivastava final project
# Performing analysis on stock market data

Part 1: Data Collection and Organization¶

The goal of this project is to highlight the effects of the Coronavirus on the stock market. To accurately do this, we will analyze the companies in the S&P500, a collection of the 500 highest market cap companies in the world. A company’s market cap, short for its “market capitalization”, is the total value of a company calculated by multiplying the number of shares the company has by the price of each share. Since stock prices can fluctuate quite a bit however, once a company gets into the S&P 500, it is guaranteed a spot on that list for at least a quarter of a year. The S&P 500 companies analyzed in this project are from the last quarter of 2020. More details on the topic of stocks, the S&P 500, stock analysis, and the Coronavirus can be found at the following links, respectively: https://www.investor.gov/introduction-investing/investing-basics/investment-products/stocks https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%26P_500_Index https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/stock-analysis.asp https://www.who.int/health-topics/coronavirus

The first part of the data collection process is to get an updated list of all companies and their associated tickers from an up to date website. To do this, I scraped the data from the wikipedia article linked in the beginning of this tutorial about the S&P 500. A ticker is a 1-5 character abbreviation used to represent a company in the stock market. I need the tickers to perform later requests to yahoo finance to get more data on the stocks of each company in the S&P 500.

In [10]:
# Get the tickers and names of all S&P 500 companies
rs = (grequests.get(u) for u in ['http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_S%26P_500_companies'])
soup = BeautifulSoup(grequests.map(rs)[0].text, 'lxml')
table = soup.find('table', {'class': 'wikitable sortable'})
tickers = []
for row in table.findAll('tr')[1:]:
    tickers.append(row.findAll('td')[0].text[:-1])
    
names = []
for row in table.findAll('tr')[1:]:
    names.append(row.findAll('td')[1].text)

tickers = list(filter(lambda ticker: '.' not in ticker, tickers))
tickers

The next part of the data collection process is to get data on each S&P 500 company’s stock price, price to earnings ratio, market cap, volume, and earnings per share. I used the yahoo finance quote page for each ticker in the list of tickers from above to format the proper url and scrape the necessary data.

In [11]:
# Get surface level data from yahoo finance on all tickers by performing web scraping
req_urls = []
for ticker in tickers:
    req_urls.append('https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/' + ticker)

rs = (grequests.get(u) for u in req_urls)
ticker_responses = grequests.map(rs)

Now that I have the quote data, I need to parse it. For this step, I loop through each response associated with each ticker from the above yahoo finance requests and parse out the current price. Then, I append the list of current prices as a column to a newly created dataframe containing columns for Ticker, Company Name, and Current Price.

In [12]:
# Parse current price data into dataframe
stock_data = pd.DataFrame()
stock_data['Ticker'] = pd.Series(tickers)
stock_data['Name'] = pd.Series(names)

ticker_prices = []
for res in ticker_responses:
    ticker_soup = BeautifulSoup(res.text, 'lxml')
    try:
        ticker_prices.append(ticker_soup.find('div', {'data-reactid': '49'}).find("span").text)
    except:
        ticker_prices.append(np.nan)
    
stock_data['Current Price'] = pd.Series(ticker_prices)
stock_data

Next, I need to parse out the rest of the quote data. I used the same process as the part above to parse the P/E ratio, market cap, trade volume, and earnings per share into the dataframe.

In [13]:
# Parse PE ratios, market caps, trading volumes and EPS into the dataframe

ticker_pe_ratios = []
ticker_mcap = []
ticker_volume = []
ticker_eps = []
for res in ticker_responses:
    ticker_soup = BeautifulSoup(res.text, 'lxml')
    ticker_pe_ratios.append(ticker_soup.find('table', {'class': 'W(100%) M(0) Bdcl(c)'}).find('td', {'data-test': 'PE_RATIO-value'}).text)
    ticker_mcap.append(ticker_soup.find('table', {'class': 'W(100%) M(0) Bdcl(c)'}).find('td', {'data-test': 'MARKET_CAP-value'}).text)
    ticker_volume.append(ticker_soup.find('table', {'class': 'W(100%)'}).find('td', {'data-test': 'TD_VOLUME-value'}).text)
    ticker_eps.append(ticker_soup.find('table', {'class': 'W(100%) M(0) Bdcl(c)'}).find('td', {'data-test': 'EPS_RATIO-value'}).text)

    

stock_data['P/E Ratio'] = pd.Series(ticker_pe_ratios)
stock_data['Market Cap'] = pd.Series(ticker_mcap)
stock_data['Volume'] = pd.Series(ticker_volume)
stock_data['EPS'] = pd.Series(ticker_eps)
stock_data

Now that the quote data has been parsed, it’s time to get some more interesting data. To do this, I will perform the same process of requesting data from yahoo finance as I did for the quote data, but this time I will be getting historical data. The specific data I am getting is the stock price on the first of the month for every month in the past year for each of the 500 companies in our analysis. This request is also done asynchronously to improve the efficiency of this portion of the data collection.

In [14]:
# Get historical data on all tickers from yahoo finance

req_urls = []
hist_data_url = '/history?period1=1577750400&period2=1607299200&interval=1mo&filter=history&frequency=1mo&includeAdjustedClose=true'
for ticker in tickers:
    req_urls.append('https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/' + ticker + hist_data_url)

rs = (grequests.get(u) for u in req_urls)
history_responses = grequests.map(rs)

Now that I have made all the requests for the historical data and gotten my responses, I need to once again parse out the data from the scraped HTML. To do this, I go through each get response, extract the data, and put it into an ordered list, with the first element being january 1st and the last being december 1st. Then, that list is added to a list of lists, which is then added as a column of the dataframe.

In [15]:
# Parse historical data into dataframe

parse_only_hist = SoupStrainer('table', {'data-test': 'historical-prices'})
hist_data = [[]]
for res in history_responses:
    hist_soup = BeautifulSoup(res.text, 'lxml', parse_only=parse_only_hist)
    all_closes = map(lambda r: r.text, hist_soup.find_all('td', {'class': 'Py(10px) Pstart(10px)'}))
    all_closes = list(map(lambda t: t[1], list(filter(lambda r: r[0] % 6 == 3, enumerate(all_closes)))))
    hist_data.append(all_closes[::-1])
    
stock_data['Historical Prices'] = pd.Series(hist_data[1:])
stock_data

The final piece of data we want is which sector the company operates in. To do this, I will do one final round of yahoo finance requests, this time to the profile page of each of the 500 tickers. Also, once again the requests are asynchronous to improve the efficiency of the requests.

In [16]:
# Get the sector of each ticker

req_urls = []
for ticker in tickers:
    req_urls.append('https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/' + ticker + '/profile')
    
rs = (grequests.get(u) for u in req_urls)
sector_responses = grequests.map(rs)

Finally, I parse the sector data out of the HTML responses for each response, adding the sector to a list or adding N/A if the sector is not available. That list is then added as a column to the dataframe, and the data is finally prepared for analysis.

In [17]:
# Parse sector data into dataframe

sector_data = []
for res in sector_responses:
    sector_soup = BeautifulSoup(res.text, 'lxml')
    try:
        sector_data.append(sector_soup.find('div', {'class': 'Mb(25px)'}).find('span', {'class': 'Fw(600)'}).text)
    except:
        sector_data.append("N/A")
    
stock_data['Sector'] = pd.Series(sector_data)
stock_data

Description of the stock_data dataframe: Column 1: Ticker: Ticker for the associated company in the S&P500 Column 2: Name: Name of the Company Column 3: Current Price: Current trading price of the company Column 4: P/E Ratio: Price to earnings ratio of the company Column 5: Market Cap: Market cap of the associated company Column 6: Volume: Trading volume of the associated company Column 7: EPS: Earnings per share of the associated company Column 8: Historical Prices: List of 12 prices which represent the closing prices on the first day of the month since january 1st 2020. The first element of the list is the closing price on jan 1st, the second is closing price on feb 1st, etc. Column 9: Sector: The sector of the associated company

To run the above code, first run '!pip install html5lib lxml grequests' in a cell above the import cell

Analysis: By Sector¶

Restructuring the Data¶

In order to analyze the recovery of each sector, we will aggregate each company's Historical Price data by sector.

In [18]:
sector_price_data = {}
companies_per_sector = {}
for row in stock_data.iloc:
    if row['Sector'] not in sector_price_data.keys():
        sector_price_data[row['Sector']] = []
        companies_per_sector[row['Sector']] = 1
    else:
        companies_per_sector[row['Sector']] += 1
        for i, x in enumerate(row):
            if x == '-':
                sector_price_data[i] = sector_price_data[i-1]
            
    sector_price_data[row['Sector']].append([float(x.replace(',', '')) for x in row['Historical Prices'] if x != '-'])

Price Recovery¶

Now that we see that the main sell-off stages of this year began in February and March, we know that January will be the best indicator for pre-coronavirus sell off prices in each sector. We will average the price of each sector from January 1st and December 1st. Our goal here is to check the average recovery of each sector by comparing the pre-coronavirus sell off stock prices with the stock prices from the beginning of this month.

In [20]:
pre_corona_sector_avg = {}
post_corona_sector_avg = {}

for s in sector_price_data.keys():
    pre_corona_sector_avg[s] = 0
    post_corona_sector_avg[s] = 0
    for x in sector_price_data[s]:
        pre_corona_sector_avg[s] += x[0]
        post_corona_sector_avg[s] += x[-1]
    pre_corona_sector_avg[s]  = pre_corona_sector_avg[s]/len(sector_price_data[s])
    post_corona_sector_avg[s] = post_corona_sector_avg[s]/len(sector_price_data[s])

Now that we have the pre-sell-off and post-sell-off average sector stock price data, we will divide the post-sell-off price by the pre-sell-off average. This will give make comparing different sector data to one another by putting the on a scale relative to their original price. This will account for inherent differences in sector volatility. From the plot we should be able to determine which sectors recovered the best from the coronavirus market sell-offs. In the plot below, sectors with a recovery rate of [0, 1] are marked with red circles and those with a recovery rate of (1, positive infinity) are marked with green triangles.

In [21]:
sectors = sector_price_data.keys()
g_sectors = []
g_values  = []

r_sectors = []
r_values  = []

recovery_dict = {}
for s in sectors:
    recovery = post_corona_sector_avg[s]/pre_corona_sector_avg[s]
    if recovery > 1.:
        g_sectors.append(recovery)
        g_values.append(s)
    else:
        r_sectors.append(recovery)
        r_values.append(s)
    recovery_dict[s] = recovery

plt.barh(g_values, g_sectors, color='g')
plt.barh(r_values, r_sectors, color='r')
plt.xlabel('Recovery Rate')
plt.show()

Earnings Per Share¶

The next metric that we will consider is earnings per share (eps). Earnings per share is the amount of profit the company makes divided by the number of outstanding shares. EPS above 0 means that the company is profitable, and EPS below 0 means the company is losing money. By plotting the average EPS (x-axis) of each sector against each sector's average recovery rate (y-axis) we can see whether there is a correlation between the profitability of a company and their ability to recover from the coronavirus market sell-offs.

Learn more about EPS here: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/eps.asp

Price to Earnings (P/E) Ratio¶

The next metric that we will consider is the price to earnings ratio (p/e). Price to earnings is the price of a share of company stock divided by the earnings per share of that company. The higher the p/e ratio the more you have to pay for the profit of that company. For example, two companies may have the same earnings per share, but due to a variety of reasons one stock may have a higher price than the other: a company may be surrounded by excessive hype due to a good press release, one company may be faster growing that then other and that growth may be priced in and thus increase the p/e ratio, etc...

Below we will plot the average p/e ratio of each sector against the average recovery rate of the sector.

Learn more about P/E ratio here: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/price-earningsratio.asp

Healthcare - Price Recovery¶

Next, we will examine the stock price recovery of these 10 companies by plotting the metric that results from dividing a company's December stock price by its January stock price. Using this pre and post coronavirus data in this way will give us company data on a scale relative to the company's original price. This will allow us to see which companies recovered best from the cornovirus market sell offs in the healthcare sector. Keep in mind that the 10 companies that were chosen to be examined within the sector were chosen based on this metric - we included the 5 best recovered companies and the 5 worst recovered companies.

Financial Services - Price Recovery¶

Next, we will examine the stock price recovery of these 10 companies by plotting the metric that results from dividing a company's December stock price by its January stock price. Using this pre and post coronavirus data in this way will give us company data on a scale relative to the company's original price. This will allow us to see which companies recovered best from the cornovirus market sell offs in the financial services sector. Keep in mind that the 10 companies that were chosen to be examined within the sector were chosen based on this metric - we included the 5 best recovered companies and the 5 worst recovered companies.

        g_companies.append(row['Name'])

        r_companies.append(row['Name'])

Conclusions¶

Overall, it is evident that there are seemingly endless patterns, trends, and influencing factors available to observe when it comes to stocks and how their various aspects fluctuate. One of the most standout observations from our analyses was undoubtedly the striking crash that the energy sector experience towards the beginning of this year. Initial analyses like ours allow for discovery of such occurrences. The next step in the case of such a notable discovery would have been to use statistical investigation to dig deeper into the crash and potentially discover some major causes/influencing factors. These subsequent more in-depth analyses would require more time and more data of course. Another interesting thing to note is that we chose to analyze within sectors by looking at the top and bottom 5 companies in that sector. The determination of how to define ranking ultimately ended up being price recovery ratio for us, which also contributed to interesting analysis. Using that as a ranking metric allows for several strange trends and observations to be made when comparing companies, which tells us that although insightful, maybe using price recovery as a ranking measure was not the best for simply observable patterns due to its peculiar relationship with other stock facets. At the end of the day the two most significant takeaways from this project and our analyses are that the COVID year has had a wide variety of impacts depending on the sector, and the deeper you analyze the more you find to keep investigating!
